Sorry "Jack" and yesterday morning, added back to shorts: Sep 03, 2020 | 09:46 AM EDT DOUG KASS Adding to Net Short Exposure I have moved back up from medium sized to large sized in my (SPY) and (QQQ) shorts (that was quick!). As mentioned earlier, I added to my Apple (AAPL)

and Tesla (TSLA) shorts this morning (I previously added to Tesla in the last two days). Flexibility, thank you Stan Druckenmiller. I am, however, maintaining my medium sized (SDS) long -- and I don't plan to raise the size. With my bank adds, I am maintaining the

(thus far quite premature) view that a pivot to value from growth may occur. If I am correct in view, there is a lot of downside to large-cap tech. Position: Long SDS, TSLA puts. Short SPY large, QQQ large, AAPL, TSLA Blocked and reported, again. @threadreaderapp unroll

And for those haters that listen (without questioning) to the Fin media and talking heads who never admit to being wrong, are materially in the herd of consensus and are woefully influenced by stock prices (prices have a way of changing sentiment h/t@hmeisler) I suggest you

get a copy of the 8k word column I wrote on @realmoney at 430AM yesterday morning "Did I Have My Stan Druckenmiller Moment Wednesday?" realmoney.thestreet.com/doug… I work my ass off to provide something different than the consensus - been doing it in 15 columns a day on @reamoney

since 1998 As I write, the investment mosaic is complex, far more complicated than looking a mono variables (e.g unsual call activity, etc.) Emphasizing your winners and sweeping your losers under the rug is a distinguishing trait of many. Fin media, by and large, delivers the

"happy talk" - like herds of animals on the prairie. But "group stink" can have an awful odor. Consider the contrary, always when making trading/investment decisions! Mr. Market humbles us all, never forget that. If you do forget it you will be screwed by him.
